 disenchantment of an emigrant to Manitoba who longed to move on to North Dakota. Their tone may be lyrical, elegaic, or satirical. Songs from various parts of the new world – the Carolinas, Nova Scotia, Prince Edward Island, Ontario, and the Canadian west – are included in Gaelic with a facing English translation. A short biography of each bard prefaces the selections attributed to him or her. Detailed notes provide a guide to sources and variant texts, elucidate obscure passages, and define the social and cultural context in which the songs originated. An appendix reproduces the tunes for nine of these songs.This is a book that will inform and entertain both the specialist and the general reader.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEnglish poetryvTranslations from Gaelic. 0aPoets, GaeliczCanadavBiography. 0aPoets, GaeliczUnited StatesvBiography. 0aScotsxMusicxNorth America. 0aScotszNorth AmericavMusic. 0aScottish Gaelic poetryvTranslations into English. 0aScottish Gaelic poetryxTranslations into EnglishxNorth America. 0aScottish Gaelic poetryzNorth AmericavTranslations into English. 0aSongs, Scottish GaelicxTextsxNorth America. 0aSongs, Scottish GaeliczCanadavTexts. 0aSongs, Scottish GaeliczNorth AmericavTexts. 0aSongs, Scottish GaeliczUnited StatesvTexts. 7aMUSIC / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148758589140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487585891423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487585891.jpg  a978-3-11-049094-7  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999c1933d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPA